## Session Discipline

**Every new task — even the second or third in the same session — must re-match the route below before acting.** Re-matching is cheap and catches the most common error: a new task that belongs to a different route than the last one.

- **Re-match the route every task** (scan Common Tasks / `routing.yaml`). Never assume the new task uses the last route.
- **Re-read the route's files only when the route changed, or context was compacted** (a fresh SKILL.md injection from your SessionStart hook is the signal context was dropped). Otherwise the files you read last task are still in context — re-reading them every task is wasted work and the main per-task tax this skill exists to avoid.
- **Use minimal sufficient context** — start with Always Read + route `required_reads` + workflow. Expand only on signals from `rules/agent-behavior.md` § 4; tasks beyond one clear action/check then follow `workflows/task-execution.md`, while Simple tasks skip it.
- **If you cannot tell whether context was compacted, re-read** — partial memory is worse than no memory.
- Before final validation/commit after a long or interrupted task, run `protocol-blocks/reboot-check.md`: restate the original user constraints and chosen route; if you cannot, re-read the request, the route's files, and the workflow before proceeding.

**Route-before-routing check (Principle 1 gate)** — if the request contains vague improvement verbs ("refactor / clean up / optimize / make it better / 整理 / 重构 / 优化") **without** a concrete module, file, or verifiable outcome, **stop and ask** for scope before matching below. Offering partial plans, scanning the project "to get started", or proposing options is forbidden — the gate blocks forward movement until scope is clarified. See `protocol-blocks/ambiguous-request-gate.md` for full protocol.

</always-applicable>

